1. Genes connected to language and cognition

Researchers have identified a few genes strongly associated with speech and brain development. The most famous is:

FOXP2

FOXP2 regulates other genes involved in neural circuits for speech and motor coordination.

When it’s mutated in humans, people often show:
	•	difficulty producing speech
	•	trouble with grammar
	•	impaired sequence learning

Interestingly, versions of FOXP2 exist in many animals (birds, mice, etc.), but the human version has two key mutations compared to chimpanzees.

Those small differences appear to influence brain development in regions tied to language.

But FOXP2 alone isn’t enough — it’s more like a switch in a larger network.

⸻

Other genes researchers look at

A few others that appear in studies:

Gene	Possible role
SRGAP2	neuron development and cortical expansion
HAR1	brain development during fetal growth
CNTNAP2	neural connectivity and language processing

None of them create language by themselves. Instead they affect neural wiring patterns.

