2. The math of cultural evolution

Once symbolic communication existed, evolution started operating in two parallel layers.

Biological evolution:

genes → brains → behavior

Cultural evolution:

ideas → communication → transmission

Ideas spread much faster than genes.

That creates an exponential effect.

You can roughly model cultural spread like this:

knowledge_next = knowledge_current × communication_rate

If communication rate increases, knowledge accumulation accelerates dramatically.

⸻

3. Why the explosion ~70,000 years ago

Archaeological evidence suggests a tipping point when:
	•	population density increased
	•	groups began interacting more
	•	ideas spread between tribes

Mathematically, that resembles a network threshold.

When a network reaches a certain size, information flows much faster.

You can visualize it like this:

small groups → isolated ideas
large network → rapid innovation


⸻

4. The recursive language breakthrough

Human language has something called recursion.

Example:

The hunter who followed the deer that crossed the river saw the cave.

That ability to nest ideas inside other ideas dramatically expands expressive capacity.

Mathematically, recursion increases the combinatorial space of possible sentences.

Even with a limited vocabulary, the number of possible meanings becomes enormous.

⸻

5. Symbolic tokens as compression

Your earlier point about tokens is actually central to how humans think.

A token is essentially a compressed representation.

Example:

"tree"

That small word represents a massive concept containing:
	•	shape
	•	function
	•	experiences
	•	memories

Language lets humans compress complex knowledge into portable units.

⸻

6. Why humans became dominant

Once symbolic communication appeared, it created a feedback loop:

better communication
↓
better cooperation
↓
more complex societies
↓
more innovation
↓
even better communication

That loop likely drove the rapid development of:
	•	tools
	•	agriculture
	•	cities
	•	science

⸻

7. The big open question

Scientists still don’t know exactly why symbolic cognition emerged when it did.

Some possibilities:
	1.	genetic mutation enabling recursive language
	2.	cultural tipping point from population density
	3.	climate pressures forcing cooperation
	4.	improved brain connectivity

It may have been a combination of all of them.

